<p>
The theory of solution is given in the previous sections. In this section we are going to see application of the method for Fredholm integro-differential equations.
</p>

<p>
<b>The Noise Terms Phenomena </b>
</p>

<p>
The exact solution of any integral or integro-differential equation, might be
obtained by considering the 1<sup>st</sup> two components u<sub>0</sub> and u<sub>1</sub> only. Instead of
evaluating several terms, it is useful to examine the 1st two components u<sub>0</sub> and u<sub>1</sub>.
</p>

<p>
If we observe the appearance of like terms in both components with opposite sign,
then by canceling these terms, the remaining non-canceled terms of u<sub>0</sub> might in some cases provide the exact solution. This can be justified through substitution.
The self-canceling terms between u<sub>0</sub> and u<sub>1</sub> are called noise terms.
</p>

<p>
If the noise terms cannot be computable, then several components are evaluated then solution is written in the series form.
</p>

